@article{watanabe:1989,
	Abstract = {We describe an attempt to derive an effective pair potential for rigid water molecules that incorporates polarization in a meanfield approximation. The potential parameters have been adjusted to fit the position of the first peak in the oxygen-oxygen pair distribution function at room temperature, the experimental density and energy, and the dielectric constant of the liquid. The properties of this potential are compared and contrasted with those of two other commonly used effective pair potentials, namely the SPC and TIP4P potentials, each of which fails to give a good fit to the oxygen-oxygen radial distribution function. Some comparisons are also made with the properties of the flexible SPC water potential and the SPC/E potential that was the first rigid molecule potential to account correctly for the mean field self-polarization. The inter-comparison between these potentials highlights the difficulty of achieving a quantitative fit to the properties of water within the pair potential approximation. Particular attention is given to the dielectric properties of the models.},
